THE PILOT ENTERED 9,380-FOOT LA VETA PASS AT 8,000 FEET MSL. HE SAID HE 
ENCOUNTERED TURBULENCE AND DOWNDRAFTS AS HE APPROACHED THE SUMMIT, 
AND THE AIRPLANE 'COULDN'T GENERATE ANY LIFT' AND STALLED. MOMENTS 
AFTER THE ACCIDENT, ANOTHER PILOT REPORTED OCCASIONAL MODERATE TO 
EXTREME TURBULENCE IN THE VICINITY. 
THE PILOT'S IMPROPER INFLIGHT DECISION TO ENTER A MOUNTAIN PASS AT AN 
INADEQUATE ALTITUDE, CAUSING THE AIRCRAFT'S CLIMB PERFORMANCE TO BE 
EXCEEDED. FACTORS WERE TURBULENCE AND DOWNDRAFTS. 
